summary: I was thinking and you know how they kept making opposite scenes? like the scene in which the "new konstantin" asks Villanelle...
question: I was thinking and you know how they kept making opposite scenes? like the scene in which the "new konstantin" asks Villanelle to sit down ad she denies, but then Eve asks her and she acts like a Little puppy. I remembered this scene where she describes to Frank what happens when you die in a completely terrifying and sadistic way and I'm thinking that maybe they'll do an opposite of that if the Little boy from the spoiler asks her ,as a sign of empathy from V. If they do that I'll bawl.
answer:
i think that this season’s theme is going to be ‘control.’ @theatrelesbabe and i have talked about it extensively. 

villanelle’s entire life up until this point has been about keeping control. eve makes her lose that control. even when she didn’t know who eve was in the bathroom, meeting her threw villanelle off her game, and she ended up massacring everyone on the hospital floor instead of making it look like a suicide. she hates that eve makes her lose control yet relishes in it at the same time. 

on the other hand, eve is losing control of her entire life. she’s desperately clinging onto anything that can help her gain it back, which means getting back to familiarity, getting back with niko. she’s soon going to realize she’s not able to go back to her old life. 

villanelle relinquishes control, and eve just loses it. conscious vs unconscious. 

i would love for them to highlight villanelle’s growing empathy with the little boy. she’s relinquishing the control of her feelings. she used to carefully monitor them to make sure she didn’t get hurt, to make sure she couldn’t feel anything. now, she’s feeling shit, and she’s becoming okay with it. 

im psyched to see this whole new side of her be explored. she’s such a complex and interesting person. im also psyched for learning more about eve because, to be honest, we know absolutely nothing about her. although i have some ideas.

summary: I recommended Killing Eve to my nephew. but he's currently catching up on game of thrones, i hope he watches KE S2 instead of...
question: I recommended Killing Eve to my nephew. but he's currently catching up on game of thrones, i hope he watches KE S2 instead of GOT's last season. because KE needs those ratings more.
answer:
true facts. im hoping bc they are doing so much advertising and press and the switch to amc that the show will get really good ratings this season. sandra oh’s star power draws a lot of people to the show, along with these awards she’s been raking in. 

i have a lot of faith in this season but don’t worry about GOT. it airs an hour after KE so your nephew can watch both!

summary: The fact that Villanelle can make it seem as if Eve’s in control but shifts that illusion with just a single word because when...
caption:
The fact that Villanelle can make it seem as if Eve’s in control but shifts that illusion with just a single word because when she says “please” she’s offering Eve the cake that Villanelle didn’t make; in a place that Villanelle doesn’t own.

She just takes control of everything. It’s also fascinating to watch how Eve responds to this because Eve doesn’t actually need to be told to get some for herself, and yet she sits there and responds to the “please” by putting pie on her own plate. Like, even with information she has - Villanelle’s name - she doesn’t know how to act. That makes her actions quite bold if you’d ask me.
